"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 29–30
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-29-30.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json (verse inventory)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing; merge_comm skips present entries)

Key Christological decisions:
- 29:2-10 Well scene: Jacob rolling the stone from the well is a type of Christ rolling
  away the stone from the tomb (Matt 28:2) and opening the source of living water (John
  4:14). The stone blocking the well = the stone blocking the tomb; the shepherd opening
  it for his flock = Christ the Good Shepherd.
- 29:18-20 Jacob's seven-year service for Rachel: the bridegroom who suffers for his
  bride is the type of Christ's incarnation and death for the church (Eph 5:25).
- 29:31-35 Leah's unloved state and her sons: God opens the unloved wife's womb; the
  unloved Leah bears Judah, the messianic ancestor. "God has chosen the foolish/weak"
  (1 Cor 1:27) — through the unloved comes the one who receives ultimate praise.
  Judah = "praise the LORD"; through him comes the one whom "every tongue" praises
  (Phil 2:11). The Levi through Leah establishes the priestly tribe.
- 30:22-24 "God remembered Rachel" — Joseph born: the divine remembering (same verb
  as Gen 8:1) opens the barren womb; Joseph's birth begins the richest Christ-type
  narrative in Genesis. Joseph beloved/betrayed/imprisoned/exalted = Christ's pattern.
- 30:37-43 Jacob's flock strategy: guided by God (31:10-12 reveals dream guidance);
  Christ as wisdom from God (1 Cor 1:30). The stronger/weaker separation = eschatological
  separation (Matt 25:32). The covenant-bearer's divinely-guided wisdom is the type.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"29": {
"1": "<p>Jacob continued on his journey and came to the land of the eastern peoples &#8212; the eastward journey to Paddan-aram begins. Jacob&#8217;s flight from Esau and journey to find a covenant wife echoes several later narrative patterns: Israel&#8217;s journey to Egypt and return, the exile and restoration. The journey east &#8212; which in Genesis consistently represents distance from the covenant land (4:16; 11:2) &#8212; is here the necessary detour before Jacob returns transformed. Christ&#8217;s descent to Bethlehem (the &#8220;east&#8221; of the heavenly dwelling) and return through resurrection is the ultimate journey-and-return through hostile territory that Jacob&#8217;s flight typologically anticipates.</p>",
"2": "<p>There Jacob saw a well in the open country, with three flocks of sheep lying near it &#8212; the well in the open country is the gathering place of shepherds and sheep. The well scene in ch29 is the third patriarchal well encounter (Abraham&#8217;s servant at the well in ch24 finds Rebekah; Moses at a well in Exod 2:15&#8211;17 meets Zipporah). The pattern &#8212; covenant-bearer arrives at a well, meets a woman, marriage follows &#8212; is a type-scene that reaches its culmination in Jesus at Jacob&#8217;s well (John 4:7&#8211;26): the bridegroom-figure meets the woman at the well, and the result is not marriage but the offer of living water and salvation to her community.</p>",
"3": "<p>When all the flocks were gathered, the shepherds would roll the stone away from the well&#8217;s mouth and water the sheep &#8212; the stone over the well&#8217;s mouth requiring collective effort to remove. The stone blocking access to the water is the type of the stone blocking the tomb (Matt 27:60; 28:2). The stone rolled away from the well enables the sheep to drink; the stone rolled away from the tomb enables the disciples to see the risen Christ and drink the living water of resurrection life. The &#8220;rolling away&#8221; language (galal) appears in both contexts; the structural parallel is one of the OT well-scenes&#8217; deepest Christological resonances.</p>",
"4": "<p>Jacob asked the shepherds, &#8220;My brothers, where are you from?&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s initiative in approaching and questioning the local shepherds. The Good Shepherd who takes initiative to know his sheep: &#8220;I know my sheep and my sheep know me&#8221; (John 10:14). Christ himself approaches, questions, and addresses both individuals and crowds &#8212; the initiating shepherd who does not wait for the sheep to come but goes to them (Luke 15:4: &#8220;Does he not leave the ninety-nine and go to search for the one lost sheep?&#8221;). Jacob&#8217;s initiative at the well is a canonical-context note on the pattern of covenant-initiative that Christ fulfills.</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;Do you know Laban, Nahor&#8217;s grandson?&#8221; &#8220;Yes, we know him,&#8221; they answered &#8212; the establishment of connection through the covenant family network. The covenant family is recognized even in distant Paddan-aram. The far-reaching name of the covenant family &#8212; Abraham&#8217;s descendants known even among distant peoples &#8212; anticipates the gospel&#8217;s reach: &#8220;For there is no distinction between Jew and Greek; for the same Lord is Lord of all, bestowing his riches on all who call on him. For everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved&#8221; (Rom 10:12&#8211;13). The name of the covenant family reaches before the family member arrives; the name of Christ reaches before his missionaries.</p>",
"6": "<p>&#8220;Is he well?&#8221; Jacob asked. &#8220;Here comes his daughter Rachel with the sheep&#8221; &#8212; the announcement of Rachel&#8217;s arrival changes the dynamic of the conversation. The arrival of the woman with the sheep at the moment the well is discussed is the narrative setup for Jacob&#8217;s well-opening act. In John 4, the Samaritan woman arrives at the well while Jesus is already there; the arrival of the woman at the well in both narratives is the moment of encounter that the well-scene pattern generates. The bridegroom-figure and the woman at the well is the recurring type of Christ and his church.</p>",
"7": "<p>Jacob said, &#8220;Look, the sun is still high; it is not time for the flocks to be gathered. Water the sheep and take them back to pasture&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s pastoral wisdom, urging that the flocks be cared for rather than idling. The concern for the welfare of the sheep is the shepherd&#8217;s defining characteristic. Christ&#8217;s pastoral concern is the fulfillment of this: &#8220;I am the good shepherd. The good shepherd lays down his life for the sheep&#8221; (John 10:11). Where Jacob urges the shepherds to care well for their flocks, Christ is the shepherd who himself bears the cost of sheep-care all the way to death.</p>",
"8": "<p>&#8220;We can&#8217;t, until all the flocks are gathered and the stone has been rolled away from the well&#8217;s mouth&#8221; &#8212; the stone over the well is the barrier that must be removed before the sheep can drink. The pastoral impossibility &#8212; the sheep need water but the stone blocks the well &#8212; is the type of the spiritual impossibility before Christ: humanity needs the living water of God but the stone of sin, death, and alienation blocks access. The rolled-away stone of the resurrection is the permanent removal of the barrier that blocked the sheep from the water of life. Christ&#8217;s resurrection is the cosmic well-opening that makes living water permanently available.</p>",
"9": "<p>While he was still talking with them, Rachel came with her father&#8217;s flock &#8212; the arrival of Rachel interrupts Jacob&#8217;s conversation with the shepherds and immediately prompts him to action (v10). The beloved&#8217;s arrival transforms the situation. In the Song of Solomon, the bridegroom&#8217;s arrival prompts immediate response (Song 2:8&#8211;10). Christ&#8217;s arrival in history transformed the entire situation of humanity: &#8220;But when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son&#8221; (Gal 4:4). The beloved&#8217;s appearance changes everything; the bridegroom&#8217;s arrival is the pivot of salvation history.</p>",
"10": "<p>When Jacob saw Rachel and the sheep, he went over and rolled the stone away from the well&#8217;s mouth and watered the flock &#8212; Jacob alone rolls away the stone that normally required all the shepherds together (v3). The extraordinary act of strength done out of love for Rachel corresponds to the extraordinary act of resurrection done by the Father for the Son: &#8220;God raised him from the dead&#8221; (Acts 2:24; 3:15; Rom 10:9). The stone rolled away by love &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s love for Rachel moving him to superhuman effort; the Father&#8217;s love moving him to raise the Son &#8212; is the structural parallel. The beloved sheep are watered because the stone is removed; the church receives living water because the tomb-stone is removed.</p>",
"11": "<p>Then Jacob kissed Rachel and began to weep aloud &#8212; the bridegroom&#8217;s overwhelming emotion at meeting his bride after the journey. The covenant love expressed in tears is the type of Christ&#8217;s deep emotional engagement with his people: &#8220;Jesus wept&#8221; (John 11:35) at Lazarus&#8217;s tomb; &#8220;he saw the city, he wept over it&#8221; (Luke 19:41) over Jerusalem. The bridegroom who weeps out of love for the beloved is the type of the Messiah whose love for his people is strong enough to produce tears &#8212; and strong enough to take him to death for them (Eph 5:25: &#8220;Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her&#8221;).</p>",
"12": "<p>Jacob told Rachel that he was a relative of her father and a son of Rebekah, and she ran and told her father &#8212; the identification of the covenant-bearer and the announcement to the household. The pattern of arrival, identification, and household-proclamation is the pattern of the gospel&#8217;s arrival: &#8220;Philip found Nathanael and told him, &#8216;We have found the one Moses wrote about in the Law, and about whom the prophets also wrote &#8212; Jesus of Nazareth&#8217;&#8221; (John 1:45). The woman who runs to tell her household about the man at the well corresponds to both Rachel here and the Samaritan woman of John 4:28&#8211;29: &#8220;Then, leaving her water jar, the woman went back to the town and said to the people, &#8216;Come, see a man who told me everything I ever did.&#8217;&#8221;</p>",
"13": "<p>Laban hurried to meet Jacob, embraced him, kissed him, and brought him home &#8212; the welcome of the covenant kinsman into the household. The reception of the covenant-bearer with embrace and household-welcome is the type of the prodigal son&#8217;s reception: &#8220;But while he was still a long way off, his father saw him and was filled with compassion for him; he ran to his son, threw his arms around him and kissed him&#8221; (Luke 15:20). Christ himself told this parable of the running father who embraces &#8212; the divine welcome of those who return to the covenant household is the gospel&#8217;s invitation. The pattern of running, embrace, and kiss at the arrival of the beloved runs from this covenant meeting to the parable&#8217;s climax.</p>",
"14": "<p>Laban said, &#8220;You are my own flesh and blood.&#8221; After Jacob had stayed with him for a whole month &#8212; &#8220;my own flesh and blood&#8221; (lit. my bone and my flesh, as in 2:23). The kinsman language is the basis of the goel (kinsman-redeemer) relationship. Christ becomes our kinsman-redeemer by taking on flesh and blood: &#8220;Since the children have flesh and blood, he too shared in their humanity so that by his death he might break the power of him who holds the power of death&#8221; (Heb 2:14). The covenant kinship language &#8220;my bone and my flesh&#8221; reaches its fullest expression in Christ&#8217;s union with the church: &#8220;For we are members of his body&#8221; (Eph 5:30 &#8212; some manuscripts: &#8220;members of his body, of his flesh and of his bones&#8221;).</p>",
"15": "<p>Laban said, &#8220;Just because you are a relative of mine, should you work for me for nothing? Tell me what your wages should be&#8221; &#8212; Laban&#8217;s reasonable-sounding offer initiates the labor negotiation that will entangle Jacob for 20 years. The fair-sounding offer that conceals exploitation is the world&#8217;s consistent engagement with the covenant-bearer. Christ warns his disciples about this: &#8220;I am sending you out like sheep among wolves. Therefore be as shrewd as snakes and as innocent as doves&#8221; (Matt 10:16). The covenant community navigating a world that offers fair wages but delivers exploitation is the perpetual challenge that Jacob&#8217;s Laban-years typify.</p>",
"16": "<p>Laban had two daughters; the name of the older was Leah, and the name of the younger was Rachel &#8212; the two daughters introduced. In the allegorical tradition, Leah and Rachel have been read as the types of the active and contemplative lives (Augustine, Gregory), or of the law-covenant (Leah, unloved) and the promise-covenant (Rachel, beloved). The typological distance between the two wives runs through the narrative: Leah bears the messianic tribe (Judah) and the priestly tribe (Levi) but is unloved; Rachel is beloved but barren until God opens her womb. God&#8217;s purposes flow through unexpected channels &#8212; the unloved, the barren &#8212; as they do through the cross: &#8220;foolishness to those who are perishing&#8221; (1 Cor 1:18) but the power of God.</p>",
"17": "<p>Leah had soft eyes, but Rachel had a lovely figure and was beautiful &#8212; the contrast in appearance between the sisters. The physical description is the narrative&#8217;s way of explaining Jacob&#8217;s preference for Rachel over Leah. The outer appearance that humans evaluate (&#8220;lovely figure and beautiful&#8221;) versus the inner spiritual significance that God emphasizes (through the unloved Leah, not the beautiful Rachel, the messianic line flows) is the contrast of 1 Sam 16:7: &#8220;The LORD does not look at the things people look at. People look at the outward appearance, but the LORD looks at the heart.&#8221; Isaiah 53:2 describes the Servant: &#8220;he had no beauty or majesty to attract us to him, nothing in his appearance that we should desire him&#8221; &#8212; like Leah, not Rachel.</p>",
"18": "<p>Jacob was in love with Rachel and said, &#8220;I will work for you seven years in return for your younger daughter Rachel&#8221; &#8212; the bridegroom who offers years of labor as the bride-price. The NT develops the bride-price of Christ in several directions: the church is &#8220;bought with a price&#8221; (1 Cor 6:20; 7:23 &#8212; the price being Christ&#8217;s blood); &#8220;the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many&#8221; (Matt 20:28). Jacob serves seven years; Christ gives his life. The bridegroom&#8217;s covenant service for his bride is the type of the incarnation-and-cross as the bride-price: &#8220;Christ loved the church and gave himself up for her&#8221; (Eph 5:25).</p>",
"19": "<p>Laban said, &#8220;It is better that I give her to you than to some other man. Stay here with me&#8221; &#8212; Laban&#8217;s acceptance of Jacob&#8217;s offer. The covenant negotiation proceeds with Laban&#8217;s apparent generosity (which will be revealed as self-interest in the Leah-deception). The acceptance of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s offer &#8212; God accepting Christ&#8217;s offering of himself &#8212; is the theological basis of the atonement. Heb 9:14: Christ &#8220;offered himself unblemished to God.&#8221; God accepted the offering: &#8220;he was heard because of his reverent submission&#8221; (Heb 5:7). The acceptance of the bridegroom&#8217;s offer is the covenant agreement from which the marriage proceeds.</p>",
"20": "<p>Jacob served seven years to get Rachel, but they seemed like only a few days to him because of his love for her &#8212; the love that transforms the experience of sacrifice. Seven years of labor experienced as days because of love is the type of Paul&#8217;s view of suffering in light of the greater glory: &#8220;our light and momentary troubles are achieving for us an eternal glory that far outweighs them all&#8221; (2 Cor 4:17). Christ&#8217;s suffering, viewed from the perspective of the resurrection glory, was endured for &#8220;the joy set before him&#8221; (Heb 12:2). The joy of the bride makes the labor seem light; the joy of the resurrection makes the cross endurable. Jacob&#8217;s seven years-as-days is the OT type of suffering transformed by love into endurable sacrifice.</p>",
"21": "<p>Jacob said to Laban, &#8220;Give me my wife. My time is completed, and I want to make her my wife&#8221; &#8212; the completion of the covenant service and the claim of the bride. The language of completion (&#8220;my time is completed&#8221;) is the type of Christ&#8217;s &#8220;It is finished&#8221; (John 19:30) &#8212; the declaration that the service/sacrifice is complete and the covenant claim can be made. The bridegroom who has completed his service and claims his bride is the type of Christ who, having completed the atonement, claims the church as his own: &#8220;to present her to himself as a radiant church, without stain or wrinkle or any other blemish, but holy and blameless&#8221; (Eph 5:27).</p>",
"22": "<p>Laban brought together all the people of the place and gave a feast &#8212; the wedding feast for Jacob and (seemingly) Rachel. The wedding feast is the central image of the kingdom of God in Jesus&#8217;s teaching: &#8220;the kingdom of heaven is like a king who prepared a wedding banquet for his son&#8221; (Matt 22:2); &#8220;many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven&#8221; (Matt 8:11). The great feast that Laban holds is the covenantal occasion of covenant-making; the eschatological feast is the ultimate occasion at which Christ claims his bride: &#8220;Blessed are those who are invited to the wedding supper of the Lamb&#8221; (Rev 19:9).</p>",
"23": "<p>But when evening came, he took his daughter Leah and brought her to Jacob &#8212; the great deception: Leah substituted for Rachel in the darkness. The man who deceived his father in the darkness (27:18&#8211;29: Jacob covered in goatskins, deceiving the blind Isaac in the dark tent) is now deceived in the darkness. The lex talionis operates through the moral order: &#8220;a man reaps what he sows&#8221; (Gal 6:7). The covenant-bearer is not exempt from the consequences of his own moral failures. Christ alone enters the consequences without deserving them: &#8220;God made him who had no sin to be sin for us&#8221; (2 Cor 5:21). Jacob receives what he sowed; Christ receives what sinners sowed.</p>",
"24": "<p>Laban gave his servant Zilpah to his daughter as her attendant &#8212; the attendant given with the bride is a narrative detail that sets up Zilpah&#8217;s role in ch30. The attendant servant is part of the bride&#8217;s dowry. The detail also parallels the gift of Bilhah to Rachel (v29). The household structure of the covenant family &#8212; with its complex network of wives, servants, and children &#8212; is the fallen-world context in which the covenant promise must be worked out. Christ enters this messy world: &#8220;the Word became flesh and made his dwelling among us&#8221; (John 1:14) &#8212; not in a sanitized covenant community but in the actual fallen households of actual human families.</p>",
"25": "<p>When morning came, there was Leah! Jacob said to Laban, &#8220;What is this you have done to me? I served you for Rachel, didn&#8217;t I?&#8221; &#8212; the morning revelation of deception. The light of morning reveals what the darkness concealed. The gospel similarly brings the light that reveals hidden things: &#8220;He will bring to light what is hidden in darkness and will expose the motives of the heart&#8221; (1 Cor 4:5). But Jacob&#8217;s anguish at the morning revelation &#8212; expecting Rachel, finding Leah &#8212; is the type of the disciples&#8217; desolate morning-after on Holy Saturday: expecting the Kingdom, finding death. The resurrection morning reverses Jacob&#8217;s experience: arriving at the tomb expecting death, finding life.</p>",
"26": "<p>Laban replied, &#8220;It is not our custom here to give the younger daughter in marriage before the older one&#8221; &#8212; Laban&#8217;s rationalization of his deception. The custom he invokes (older before younger) is exactly the covenant order that God has consistently reversed: Ishmael before Isaac, Esau before Jacob, and now this reversal forced on Jacob himself. The pattern of divine reversal &#8212; the younger/lesser honored before the older/greater &#8212; runs through the entire patriarchal narrative and reaches its climax in Christ: &#8220;the last will be first, and the first will be last&#8221; (Matt 20:16). God&#8217;s kingdom operates by a reversed order that the world&#8217;s customs cannot contain.</p>",
"27": "<p>&#8220;Finish this daughter&#8217;s bridal week; then we will give you the younger one also, in return for another seven years of work&#8221; &#8212; Jacob must serve 14 years total for his bride. The doubled labor-price for the beloved bride is the type of Christ&#8217;s extravagant giving for the church. Paul in Eph 5:25 says Christ &#8220;gave himself up&#8221; for the church &#8212; the entire self, not a portion. The covenant commitment that expands beyond the original agreement, giving more rather than withdrawing, is the type of grace that exceeds expectation: &#8220;where sin increased, grace increased all the more&#8221; (Rom 5:20). God&#8217;s covenant commitment to his people is not reduced by the difficulty of the situation.</p>",
"28": "<p>Jacob did so. He finished the week with Leah, and then Laban gave him his daughter Rachel to be his wife &#8212; the covenant fulfilled: after the extended service, Rachel. The pattern of covenant promise &#8212; delay &#8212; fulfillment is the redemptive-historical arc of the entire OT: the covenant is promised, the fulfillment delayed, and then &#8220;when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son&#8221; (Gal 4:4). Jacob endures the delay with both Leah and the additional seven years; Christ endures the cross before entering his glory (Luke 24:26: &#8220;Did not the Messiah have to suffer these things and then enter his glory?&#8221;). The completion of the service and the receiving of the bride is the shape of the gospel&#8217;s denouement.</p>",
"29": "<p>Laban gave his servant Bilhah to his daughter Rachel as her attendant &#8212; the servant given with Rachel is a detail that sets up Bilhah&#8217;s role as Rachel&#8217;s surrogate in ch30 (vv3&#8211;8). The household details of the covenant family are recorded with care, as they generate the twelve tribes through whom the covenant history proceeds to Christ. The genealogical importance of these household arrangements &#8212; however morally complex &#8212; shows that God&#8217;s covenant purposes work through and despite the messiness of fallen human family structures.</p>",
"30": "<p>Jacob&#8217;s love for Rachel was greater than his love for Leah. And he worked for Laban another seven years &#8212; the continued service for another seven years after receiving Rachel, fulfilling the full 14-year commitment. The covenant-bearer who serves the full term even when partially fulfilled is the type of Christ&#8217;s complete and unreserved self-offering. &#8220;Having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end&#8221; (John 13:1). The completeness of the covenant service &#8212; not partial but full &#8212; is the shape of Christ&#8217;s atoning work: &#8220;It is finished&#8221; (John 19:30). Nothing partial, nothing withheld.</p>",
"31": "<p>When the LORD saw that Leah was not loved, he enabled her to conceive, but Rachel remained childless &#8212; &#8220;When the LORD saw that Leah was not loved&#8221; &#8212; the divine sight of the unloved is one of the most powerful statements in the OT. The God who sees the despised and overlooked (El Roi, 16:13) acts on behalf of the unloved Leah by opening her womb. Christ consistently moves toward the unloved and overlooked: the tax collectors, the prostitutes, the lepers, the Samaritans. &#8220;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: While we were still sinners, Christ died for us&#8221; (Rom 5:8) &#8212; the love that goes to those who are not naturally lovable or beloved. The God who sees Leah&#8217;s unloved state is fully revealed in Christ who seeks the lost.</p>",
"32": "<p>Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son. She named him Reuben, for she said, &#8220;It is because the LORD has seen my misery. Surely my husband will love me now&#8221; &#8212; Reuben (&#8220;see, a son&#8221; / &#8220;the LORD has seen my misery&#8221;). The divine seeing of human misery is the theological claim behind the name. The God who sees Leah&#8217;s misery is the God who &#8220;was moved with compassion&#8221; (Matt 9:36; 14:14; 15:32) when he saw the crowds &#8212; and acted. Christ&#8217;s compassion is the fulfillment of the divine-seeing that Leah names: God saw, and sent his Son (John 3:16: &#8220;God so loved the world&#8221;). Reuben&#8217;s name testifies to God&#8217;s seeing even before it sees the full expression of that seeing in Christ.</p>",
"33": "<p>She named him Simeon, for she said, &#8220;Because the LORD heard that I am not loved, he gave me this one also&#8221; &#8212; Simeon (&#8220;he has heard&#8221;). The divine hearing that responds to the unloved is the God who &#8220;hears&#8221; prayer (Ps 34:17: &#8220;the righteous cry out, and the LORD hears them&#8221;; Matt 7:7: &#8220;Ask and it will be given to you&#8221;). Christ explicitly promises divine hearing: &#8220;Whatever you ask in my name, the Father will give you&#8221; (John 16:23). The Simeon-name &#8220;God has heard&#8221; is the OT testimony to divine responsiveness that Christ actualizes: &#8220;we know that God does not listen to sinners&#8221; (John 9:31, in the world&#8217;s view) &#8212; but through Christ, the sinner&#8217;s prayer reaches the Father (John 14:6; Heb 4:16).</p>",
"34": "<p>She named him Levi, for she said, &#8220;Now at last my husband will become attached to me, because I have borne him three sons&#8221; &#8212; Levi (&#8220;attached/joined&#8221;). The Levitical tribe, the priestly tribe of Israel, is born through the unloved Leah. The irony is profound: the tribe that mediates between God and Israel comes not through the favored line but through the despised. Christ is the high priest who came &#8220;from Judah, and in regard to that tribe Moses said nothing about priests&#8221; (Heb 7:14) &#8212; not from Levi but in the Melchizedekian order. Yet the priestly heritage that Leah&#8217;s Levi represents flows into Christ who makes all believers &#8220;a royal priesthood&#8221; (1 Pet 2:9): &#8220;you are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation.&#8221;</p>",
"35": "<p>She named him Judah, saying, &#8220;This time I will praise the LORD&#8221; &#8212; Judah (&#8220;praise the LORD&#8221; / &#8220;I will praise&#8221;). The fourth son, named for praise, becomes the messianic ancestor. From the unloved wife&#8217;s fourth son &#8212; not the firstborn, not the son of the favored wife &#8212; comes the line that leads to David and to Christ (Matt 1:2: &#8220;Judah the father of Perez and Zerah&#8221;; Luke 3:33; Heb 7:14: &#8220;our Lord descended from Judah&#8221;; Rev 5:5: &#8220;the Lion of the tribe of Judah&#8221;). The name that means &#8220;praise&#8221; belongs to the tribe through whom comes the one whom &#8220;every tongue&#8221; praises: &#8220;every tongue acknowledge that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father&#8221; (Phil 2:11). Through the unloved Leah&#8217;s praise, the source of all praise enters the world.</p>",
},
"30": {
"1": "<p>When Rachel saw that she was not bearing Jacob any children, she became jealous of her sister and said to Jacob, &#8220;Give me children, or I&#8217;ll die!&#8221; &#8212; Rachel&#8217;s jealousy of Leah&#8217;s fruitfulness and her desperate demand for children. The desperate longing for children that feels like a longing for life itself connects to the deeper spiritual longing for new birth: &#8220;unless a man is born again, he cannot see the kingdom of God&#8221; (John 3:3). The barren woman who cries for life is the type of the spiritually barren soul who cries to Christ for the life that only the Spirit gives. &#8220;Whoever wants to save their life will lose it, but whoever loses their life for me will find it&#8221; (Matt 16:25) &#8212; the life that Rachel grasps at is the life that only God can give.</p>",
"2": "<p>Jacob became angry with her and said, &#8220;Am I in the place of God, who has kept you from having children?&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s theologically correct response: only God opens the womb. The recognition that fertility is in God&#8217;s hands, not the husband&#8217;s, is the OT&#8217;s consistent theological point (Gen 16:2; 25:21; 29:31). Christ applies the same theological logic to spiritual birth: &#8220;The wind blows wherever it pleases. You hear its sound, but you cannot tell where it comes from or where it is going. So it is with everyone born of the Spirit&#8221; (John 3:8). The Spirit births new life by divine initiative, not human effort. Jacob is not in the place of God; Christ is not &#8220;in the place of God&#8221; but is God (John 1:1; 8:58), and it is precisely this that makes his giving of life authoritative.</p>",
"3": "<p>Rachel said, &#8220;Here is Bilhah, my servant. Sleep with her so that she can bear children for me&#8221; &#8212; Rachel&#8217;s Bilhah-solution is the Sarai/Hagar pattern repeated: human engineering to produce what God has promised to give in his own time and way. Paul&#8217;s allegory in Gal 4:21&#8211;31 identifies this &#8220;according to the flesh&#8221; route as the type of law-righteousness: human effort to achieve what only divine promise can supply. The human alternative to the divine promise consistently produces not the covenant inheritance but a counterfeit that complicates rather than resolves. Only God&#8217;s opening of Rachel&#8217;s womb (v22) gives the true heir; only faith in Christ gives the true righteousness.</p>",
"4": "<p>She gave him her servant Bilhah as a wife. Jacob slept with her &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s compliance with the Bilhah arrangement. The covenant-bearer&#8217;s moral complexity &#8212; complying with an arrangement that multiplies wives and complicates the household &#8212; is a reminder that the covenant promise does not depend on its bearers&#8217; moral perfection. God&#8217;s covenant purposes work through and despite human moral failure. The NT is explicit about this: Christ&#8217;s genealogy (Matt 1:1&#8211;17) includes Tamar (who played a harlot), Rahab (a Canaanite prostitute), Ruth (a Moabite), and Bathsheba (the wife of Uriah). The covenant runs through moral failure to the one who has no moral failure of his own.</p>",
"5": "<p>Bilhah became pregnant and bore Jacob a son &#8212; the birth through the surrogate. The surrogate-birth is the &#8220;according to the flesh&#8221; route to family; the Spirit-birth is the covenant route. The surrogate son is real and loved &#8212; Dan is one of the twelve tribes &#8212; but is not the child of primary promise. The distinction between genuine gifts that fall short of the central promise and the central promise itself runs through Genesis. Christ is not one among several religious options (surrogates) but the one through whom alone the promise is fulfilled: &#8220;Salvation is found in no one else&#8221; (Acts 4:12).</p>",
"6": "<p>Rachel said, &#8220;God has vindicated me; he has listened to my plea and given me a son.&#8221; Because of this she named him Dan &#8212; Dan (&#8220;he has vindicated / judged&#8221;). The divine vindication of the one who was failing &#8212; God heard Rachel&#8217;s plea &#8212; is a type of the divine vindication that Christ receives at the resurrection. 1 Tim 3:16: Christ was &#8220;vindicated by the Spirit&#8221; &#8212; the resurrection is the Father&#8217;s vindication of the Son who was apparently defeated. The God who vindicates Rachel by giving her a son vindicates Christ by raising him from the dead: &#8220;God raised him from the dead, freeing him from the agony of death, because it was impossible for death to keep its hold on him&#8221; (Acts 2:24).</p>",
"7": "<p>Rachel&#8217;s servant Bilhah conceived again and bore Jacob a second son &#8212; the second son through the surrogate. The twin sons through Bilhah (Dan and Naphtali) correspond to the twin sons through Zilpah (Gad and Asher, vv10&#8211;13). The four surrogate sons alongside the six sons of Leah and the two sons of Rachel form the twelve tribes. The twelve who come through such complex and morally fraught family arrangements become the twelve who are the foundation of God&#8217;s covenant people &#8212; and ultimately the twelve apostles who are the foundation of the new covenant community (Eph 2:20; Rev 21:14).</p>",
"8": "<p>Rachel said, &#8220;I have had a great struggle with my sister, and I have won.&#8221; So she named him Naphtali &#8212; Naphtali (&#8220;my struggle / wrestling&#8221;). The competitive struggle between Leah and Rachel &#8212; the beloved and the unloved, fighting for children and therefore for honor &#8212; is the fallen-family context of the covenant. The struggling that Rachel names her son after is the type of the spiritual warfare that runs through the covenant community&#8217;s history. Christ&#8217;s victory in Gethsemane (&#8220;Not my will, but yours be done,&#8221; Luke 22:42) is the supreme wrestling-and-winning that Naphtali&#8217;s name anticipates: the victor who wins by submission.</p>",
"9": "<p>When Leah saw that she had stopped having children, she took her servant Zilpah and gave her to Jacob as a wife &#8212; Leah&#8217;s Zilpah-arrangement mirrors Rachel&#8217;s Bilhah-arrangement: both wives using human engineering when the divine gift seems to have paused. The competitive human engineering of the two wives is the type of the &#8220;works&#8221; approach that Paul contrasts with faith: &#8220;not by works, but by him who calls&#8221; (Rom 9:11). The covenant community&#8217;s temptation is consistently to engineer by human effort what God has promised to provide by grace through faith in Christ.</p>",
"10": "<p>Leah&#8217;s servant Zilpah bore Jacob a son &#8212; the third surrogate son (second through Zilpah). The sheer complexity of the covenant family&#8217;s child-bearing arrangements &#8212; four women, twelve sons, one daughter &#8212; is the morally tangled context in which God&#8217;s covenant purposes move forward. The God who works in and through such complexity is the God of the incarnation, who enters into the full messiness of human family life: &#8220;born of a woman, born under the law&#8221; (Gal 4:4), not above the tangle but within it.</p>",
"11": "<p>Then Leah said, &#8220;What good fortune!&#8221; So she named him Gad &#8212; Gad (&#8220;good fortune / troop&#8221;). The acknowledgment of divine blessing in the birth &#8212; &#8220;good fortune&#8221; &#8212; is the appropriate response to God&#8217;s provision. The NT equivalent is &#8220;every good and perfect gift is from above, coming down from the Father of the heavenly lights&#8221; (Jas 1:17). The recognition that blessing comes from God rather than from human effort is the theological posture that Christ calls his disciples to: &#8220;Apart from me you can do nothing&#8221; (John 15:5).</p>",
"12": "<p>Leah&#8217;s servant Zilpah bore Jacob a second son &#8212; the fourth surrogate son. Each of these births, through their complexity, adds to the tribal inventory that becomes Israel&#8217;s twelve-tribe structure. The messy multiplicity that the narrative records is the raw material of God&#8217;s covenant ordering. Paul sees the whole of Israel&#8217;s complex history as the preparatory ground for Christ: &#8220;I could wish that I myself were cursed and cut off from Christ for the sake of my people&#8230; Theirs is the adoption to sonship; theirs the divine glory, the covenants, the receiving of the law&#8230; theirs the patriarchs, and from them is traced the human ancestry of the Messiah&#8221; (Rom 9:3&#8211;5).</p>",
"13": "<p>Then Leah said, &#8220;How happy I am! The women will call me happy.&#8221; So she named him Asher &#8212; Asher (&#8220;happy / blessed&#8221;). The declaration of blessedness by the unloved wife &#8212; &#8220;How happy I am!&#8221; &#8212; is the OT anticipation of the beatitudes: &#8220;Blessed are the poor in spirit&#8230; blessed are those who mourn&#8235; blessed are the meek&#8221; (Matt 5:3&#8211;5). The happiness that Leah declares despite her unloved status is the type of the joy that Christ brings to those the world overlooks: &#8220;Blessed are you who are poor, for yours is the kingdom of God&#8221; (Luke 6:20). The unloved Leah, made happy by God&#8217;s gift, is the type of the &#8220;poor in spirit&#8221; who inherit the kingdom.</p>",
"14": "<p>Reuben went out into the fields during wheat harvest and found some mandrake plants, which he brought to his mother Leah. Rachel said to Leah, &#8220;Please give me some of your son&#8217;s mandrakes&#8221; &#8212; the mandrakes (thought to have fertility properties in the ANE) are the human fertility-seeking that contrasts with divine gift. Rachel seeks mandrakes to secure what only God can give; she receives Joseph not through the mandrakes but through God&#8217;s remembering (v22). The futility of the fertility-magic is the type of all human effort to achieve by technique what only divine grace provides: &#8220;Not by might nor by power, but by my Spirit, says the LORD Almighty&#8221; (Zech 4:6). Christ gives what no mandrake can: the Spirit who produces life in the spiritually barren.</p>",
"15": "<p>Leah said, &#8220;Wasn&#8217;t it enough that you took away my husband? Will you take my son&#8217;s mandrakes too?&#8221; Rachel replied, &#8220;Very well; he can sleep with you tonight in return for your son&#8217;s mandrakes&#8221; &#8212; the mandrake-negotiation reduces Jacob to a commodity traded between his competing wives. The covenant-bearer bartered for herbs by his competing wives is a low point in the narrative. The moral dysfunction of the household is the context in which God&#8217;s purposes must proceed &#8212; not the ideal context but the actual one. Christ enters the actual: &#8220;he was numbered with the transgressors&#8221; (Isa 53:12; Mark 15:28). God&#8217;s covenant does not wait for ideal human conditions but works within the actual fallen ones.</p>",
"16": "<p>Leah met Jacob coming in from the fields and said, &#8220;You must sleep with me. I have hired you with my son&#8217;s mandrakes&#8221; &#8212; Jacob hired by his own wife with mandrakes; the reduction of covenant love to transaction. The commercial reduction of covenant relationship &#8212; the opposite of the freely-given love of God &#8212; is the world&#8217;s consistent distortion of grace. Paul contrasts this with the gospel: &#8220;to the one who works, wages are not credited as a gift but as an obligation. However, to the one who does not work but trusts God who justifies the ungodly, their faith is credited as righteousness&#8221; (Rom 4:4&#8211;5). The transactional approach that reduces relationship to wages is exactly what grace overturns in Christ.</p>",
"17": "<p>God listened to Leah, and she became pregnant and bore Jacob a fifth son &#8212; God listens to Leah and opens her womb &#8212; not in response to the mandrakes but in response to Leah herself. The divine hearing that goes around the human technique (the mandrakes that Rachel acquired) to respond directly to the person in need is the pattern of grace: it responds to the person, not the technique. The mandrakes avail Rachel nothing; God opens Leah&#8217;s womb because God listened to Leah. Christ&#8217;s response to prayer similarly bypasses technique: &#8220;This kind can come out only by prayer&#8221; (Mark 9:29). The direct divine response to the person&#8217;s cry, not to any ritual technique, is the shape of gospel prayer.</p>",
"18": "<p>Leah said, &#8220;God has rewarded me for giving my servant to my husband.&#8221; So she named him Issachar &#8212; Issachar (&#8220;reward / wages&#8221;). The divine reward for faithfulness &#8212; even the mixed faithfulness of giving a servant-wife &#8212; is noted with gratitude. The concept of divine reward is carefully maintained in the NT as an aspect of grace, not of merit: &#8220;Each person will be rewarded according to their own labor&#8221; (1 Cor 3:8), but the reward comes through and not apart from Christ&#8217;s atoning work. The blessing that Leah calls &#8220;reward&#8221; is God&#8217;s free gift to the one who sought him, anticipating the promise of reward to those who seek Christ: &#8220;he rewards those who earnestly seek him&#8221; (Heb 11:6).</p>",
"19": "<p>Leah conceived again and bore Jacob a sixth son &#8212; the sixth son of Leah. The counting of sons &#8212; first through sixth for Leah, with the surrogate sons interspersed &#8212; is the genealogical precision that ensures no tribe is missed. The careful counting of the twelve builds the structure that Jesus reconstitutes in the twelve apostles (Matt 10:2&#8211;4). The &#8220;twelve&#8221; of Israel and the &#8220;twelve&#8221; of the apostles are explicitly linked in Matt 19:28 and Rev 21:12&#8211;14: the twelve gates bear the names of the twelve tribes; the twelve foundations bear the names of the twelve apostles. Both twelves point to Christ who stands at the center of both Israel and the church.</p>",
"20": "<p>Leah said, &#8220;God has presented me with a precious gift. This time my husband will treat me with honor, because I have borne him six sons.&#8221; She named him Zebulun &#8212; Zebulun (&#8220;honor / dwelling&#8221;). Leah&#8217;s hope that six sons will finally bring her husband&#8217;s honor is the poignant longing of the unloved for recognition. The longing to be honored by one&#8217;s spouse is fulfilled in Christ&#8217;s love for the church: &#8220;Husbands, love your wives, just as Christ loved the church&#8221; (Eph 5:25). Christ honors his people: &#8220;To him who overcomes, I will give&#8230; I will acknowledge their name before my Father&#8221; (Rev 3:5). The unloved Leah longing for honor receives it from the God who sees her; Christ gives the church the honor that the world withholds.</p>",
"21": "<p>Some time later she gave birth to a daughter and named her Dinah &#8212; Dinah (&#8220;vindication / justice&#8221;) is born to Leah. The daughter born to the unloved wife will be the subject of the tragedy in ch34 (Dinah&#8217;s assault and its aftermath). The vulnerability of the covenant family&#8217;s daughter in the surrounding culture is a type of the vulnerability of all who are &#8220;foreigners and strangers&#8221; (1 Pet 2:11) in the world. Christ is the defender of the vulnerable: &#8220;he has looked on the humble estate of his servant&#8221; (Luke 1:48); &#8220;he was moved with compassion&#8221; for those who had no shepherd (Matt 9:36).</p>",
"22": "<p>Then God remembered Rachel; he listened to her and enabled her to conceive &#8212; &#8220;God remembered Rachel&#8221; &#8212; the same divine-remembering verb (zakar) as Gen 8:1 (&#8220;God remembered Noah&#8221;) and Exod 2:24 (&#8220;God remembered his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob&#8221;). The divine remembering is not the end of forgetting but the beginning of covenant action: God remembered Noah &#8594; sent the wind; God remembered Rachel &#8594; opened her womb. The God who remembers is the God who acts. The fullest expression of divine remembering is the incarnation: &#8220;he has helped his servant Israel, remembering to be merciful to Abraham and his descendants forever&#8221; (Luke 1:54&#8211;55). God&#8217;s remembering of Rachel culminates in the birth of Joseph, the richest Christ-type in Genesis.</p>",
"23": "<p>She became pregnant and gave birth to a son and said, &#8220;God has taken away my disgrace&#8221; &#8212; the removal of the barren woman&#8217;s disgrace by the divine gift of a son. Elizabeth uses nearly identical language at John the Baptist&#8217;s birth: &#8220;The Lord has done this for me&#8230; In these days he has shown his favor and taken away my disgrace among the people&#8221; (Luke 1:25). The removal of disgrace through divine gift &#8212; the barren woman made fruitful, the sinner made righteous &#8212; is the gospel&#8217;s consistent pattern. Christ removes the disgrace of sin: &#8220;since we have a great high priest&#8230; let us then approach God&#8217;s throne of grace with confidence&#8221; (Heb 4:14&#8211;16). The disgrace that barrenness (physical or spiritual) brings is taken away by the divine gift of life.</p>",
"24": "<p>She named him Joseph, and said, &#8220;May the LORD add to me another son&#8221; &#8212; Joseph (&#8220;may he add / God will add&#8221;). The birth of Joseph begins the narrative that occupies the rest of Genesis (chs37&#8211;50) and constitutes the OT&#8217;s richest sustained type of Christ: the beloved son sent to his brothers, rejected and sold into slavery for silver, falsely accused, imprisoned, elevated from prison to rule over Egypt, saving his brothers who had betrayed him, forgiving and providing for them from his position of power. Every major element corresponds to Christ: &#8220;God intended it for good to accomplish what is now being done, the saving of many lives&#8221; (50:20) = &#8220;God was reconciling the world to himself in Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 5:19). Joseph&#8217;s name &#8212; &#8220;may God add&#8221; &#8212; is Rachel&#8217;s prayer for more; God answers with the &#8220;more&#8221; of the gospel.</p>",
"25": "<p>After Rachel gave birth to Joseph, Jacob said to Laban, &#8220;Send me on my way so I can go back to my own homeland&#8221; &#8212; the birth of Joseph triggers Jacob&#8217;s desire to return to Canaan &#8212; the covenant land. The completion of the family through Joseph&#8217;s birth prompts the return journey. The pattern of departure, exile, completion, and return runs through the OT&#8217;s exile-and-restoration theology and reaches its fullest expression in the incarnation-and-ascension: Christ descends from the Father, completes his mission, and returns: &#8220;I came from the Father and entered the world; now I am leaving the world and going back to the Father&#8221; (John 16:28). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s return to his homeland is the type of Christ&#8217;s return to the Father and his people&#8217;s ultimate homecoming (John 14:2&#8211;3).</p>",
"26": "<p>Jacob said, &#8220;Give me my wives and children, for whom I have served you, and I will be on my way. You know how much work I&#8217;ve done for you&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s claim on his family &#8212; those for whom he has served &#8212; is the bridegroom claiming his own. The NT develops this language for Christ&#8217;s claim on the church: &#8220;Do you not know that your bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit&#8230; You are not your own; you were bought at a price&#8221; (1 Cor 6:19&#8211;20). Christ claims the church because he has served for her: &#8220;having loved his own who were in the world, he loved them to the end&#8221; (John 13:1). The service-and-claim logic of Jacob&#8217;s 14-year labor is fulfilled in Christ&#8217;s atoning work and his claim of the church as his own.</p>",
"27": "<p>Laban said, &#8220;If I have found favor in your eyes, please stay. I have learned by divination that the LORD has blessed me because of you&#8221; &#8212; even Laban recognizes by his own methods (divination) that God has blessed him through Jacob. The blessing that flows from the covenant-bearer to the surrounding world is recognized even by those who misuse and exploit the covenant-bearer. The NT makes this explicit: the presence of the covenant community in the world is a blessing even for those who are hostile: &#8220;they saw that the LORD was with him&#8221; (Gen 39:3, of Joseph in Potiphar&#8217;s house). Christ&#8217;s presence through his people blesses the world even when the world does not acknowledge the source.</p>",
"28": "<p>He added, &#8220;Name your price, and I will pay it&#8221; &#8212; Laban offers to pay whatever Jacob asks to keep him. The world&#8217;s recognition of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s value is not the same as covenant commitment. Laban wants Jacob&#8217;s blessing-producing presence without covenant loyalty. The world&#8217;s desire for the benefits of God&#8217;s blessing without the commitment of faith is the recurring temptation that Christ addresses: those who want Jesus&#8217;s bread-multiplication (John 6:26: &#8220;you are looking for me, not because you saw the signs I performed but because you ate the loaves&#8221;) but not the demands of discipleship. &#8220;Name your price&#8221; is the world&#8217;s transactional approach to the covenant relationship.</p>",
"29": "<p>Jacob said, &#8220;You know how I have worked for you and how your livestock has fared under my care&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s account of his faithful stewardship. The steward who can account for his work is the type of Christ who gave account of his completed mission: &#8220;I have brought you glory on earth by finishing the work you gave me to do&#8221; (John 17:4). The steward&#8217;s accountability &#8212; being able to point to what was accomplished under his care &#8212; is the model of faithful service that Christ commends in the parables (Matt 25:20&#8211;21: &#8220;Master, you entrusted me with five bags of gold. See, I have gained five more&#8221;) and fulfills in his own life.</p>",
"30": "<p>&#8220;The little you had before I came has increased greatly, and the LORD has blessed you wherever I have been&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s testimony to the blessing that has come through him. The covenant-bearer as the channel of divine blessing to the surrounding world is the fulfillment of the Abrahamic promise: &#8220;all peoples on earth will be blessed through you&#8221; (12:3). The NT applies this to Christ: &#8220;For no matter how many promises God has made, they are &#8216;Yes&#8217; in Christ&#8221; (2 Cor 1:20); &#8220;Christ has become a servant of the Jews on behalf of God&#8217;s truth, so that the promises made to the patriarchs might be confirmed and&#8230; that the Gentiles might glorify God for his mercy&#8221; (Rom 15:8&#8211;9).</p>",
"31": "<p>Jacob replied, &#8220;Don&#8217;t give me anything. But if you will do this one thing for me, I will go on tending your flocks and watching over them&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s generous negotiating position: no payment, just access to the flocks on specific terms. The covenant-bearer&#8217;s generosity toward the one who has exploited him is the type of Christ&#8217;s grace toward sinners: &#8220;when we were God&#8217;s enemies, we were reconciled to him through the death of his Son&#8221; (Rom 5:10). The one who has been wronged offers generous terms to the wrongdoer, not demanding retribution but proposing covenant. This is the logic of the gospel: not &#8220;pay what you owe&#8221; but &#8220;receive what you don&#8217;t deserve.&#8221;</p>",
"32": "<p>&#8220;Let me go through all your flocks today and remove from them every speckled or spotted sheep, every dark-colored lamb&#8230; these will be my wages&#8221; &#8212; Jacob proposes the speckled-and-spotted animals as his wage, apparently a low-probability outcome from uniform Laban flocks. The covenant-bearer trusting God&#8217;s provision through an apparently unfavorable arrangement is the type of faith: &#8220;Now faith is confidence in what we hope for and assurance about what we do not see&#8221; (Heb 11:1). The arrangement that looks unpromising by human calculation but is entrusted to divine provision is the shape of covenant faith &#8212; and the shape of the cross, which looks like defeat by human calculation but is the means of cosmic victory.</p>",
"33": "<p>&#8220;And my honesty will testify for me in the future, whenever you check on the wages you have paid me. Any goat in my possession that is not speckled or spotted&#8230; will be considered stolen&#8221; &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s willingness to be audited for honesty. The transparency and accountability of the covenant-bearer, open to inspection, is the type of Christ&#8217;s claim: &#8220;Can any of you prove me guilty of sin?&#8221; (John 8:46). The integrity that welcomes examination &#8212; &#8220;my honesty will testify for me&#8221; &#8212; is the character of the one who has nothing to hide. Christ&#8217;s holiness is precisely this: open to every scrutiny, found without blemish (1 Pet 1:19: &#8220;a lamb without blemish or defect&#8221;).</p>",
"34": "<p>Laban said, &#8220;Agreed; let it be as you have said&#8221; &#8212; the covenant agreement is confirmed on Jacob&#8217;s terms. The one who has exploited the covenant-bearer now agrees to the arrangement that will result in the covenant-bearer&#8217;s prosperity. The reversal &#8212; the exploiter becomes the one who enriches the exploited through his own agreement &#8212; is the gospel&#8217;s pattern. The powers that crucified Christ thereby provided the means of universal salvation: &#8220;None of the rulers of this age understood it, for if they had, they would not have crucified the Lord of glory&#8221; (1 Cor 2:8). Satan&#8217;s exploitation of Christ becomes, by divine wisdom, the means of Satan&#8217;s own defeat.</p>",
"35": "<p>That same day Laban removed all the streaked or spotted male goats and all the speckled or spotted female goats and all the dark-colored lambs &#8212; Laban removes the very animals that were to be Jacob&#8217;s wages, apparently ensuring Jacob gets nothing. But 31:10&#8211;12 reveals that God guided Jacob&#8217;s breeding through a dream, so Laban&#8217;s manipulation was always within God&#8217;s overruling providence. The covenant-bearer disadvantaged by human manipulation but overruled by divine providence is the type of Christ&#8217;s situation at the cross: humanly manipulated, judicially murdered &#8212; but &#8220;this man was handed over to you by God&#8217;s deliberate plan and foreknowledge&#8221; (Acts 2:23). The manipulation that appears to defeat the covenant-bearer is the means of the greater divine purpose.</p>",
"36": "<p>Then Laban put a three-day journey between himself and Jacob, while Jacob continued to tend the rest of Laban&#8217;s flocks &#8212; the three-day separation between Laban and Jacob creates the space in which Jacob&#8217;s flocks will multiply. The three-day separation is yet another appearance of the three-day pattern (see 22:4; 42:18) that the NT consistently associates with the resurrection. Jacob separated from Laban for three days after which his flocks multiply; Christ separated from the disciples (dead for three days) after which the new community of the resurrection multiplies. The space of three days is consistently the space in which divine action transforms the situation.</p>",
"37": "<p>Jacob took fresh-cut branches from poplar, almond and plane trees and made white stripes on them by peeling the bark &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s breeding technique of placing striped branches in the watering troughs. Gen 31:10&#8211;12 reveals that Jacob was guided by a dream from God; the technique was divinely revealed, not merely human ingenuity. The covenant-bearer whose wisdom is divinely guided is the type of Christ &#8220;in whom are hidden all the treasures of wisdom and knowledge&#8221; (Col 2:3). The wisdom that shapes the breeding strategy is not human cleverness but divine instruction &#8212; the same pattern as Christ who &#8220;spoke only what the Father told him&#8221; (John 12:49&#8211;50).</p>",
"38": "<p>He placed the peeled branches in all the watering troughs, so that they would be directly in front of the flocks when they came to drink &#8212; the strategic placement of the branches at the point of watering. The connection of the breeding strategy to the watering troughs &#8212; the place of drink &#8212; situates the covenant-bearer&#8217;s work at the intersection of life-giving water and new generation. Christ similarly places himself at the points of spiritual life: &#8220;I am the bread of life&#8221; (John 6:35); &#8220;I am the living water&#8221; (John 4:14); &#8220;I am the resurrection&#8221; (John 11:25). The place of water is where new life is generated, in both the flocks and the people of God.</p>",
"39": "<p>The flocks mated in front of the branches and bore young that were streaked or speckled or spotted &#8212; the outcome of the divinely-guided strategy: Jacob&#8217;s wages multiply as the stronger animals produce the patterned young that belong to him. The covenant-bearer&#8217;s prosperity through God&#8217;s guidance &#8212; not through his own strength but through divinely-revealed wisdom &#8212; is the pattern of spiritual fruit-bearing: &#8220;Apart from me you can do nothing&#8230; You did not choose me, but I chose you and appointed you so that you might go and bear fruit &#8212; fruit that will last&#8221; (John 15:5, 16). The multiplication of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s portion is God&#8217;s work through the covenant-bearer, not the covenant-bearer&#8217;s work alone.</p>",
"40": "<p>Jacob set apart the young of the flock and made them face the streaked and dark-colored animals in Laban&#8217;s flock. He kept his own flocks separate and did not put them with Laban&#8217;s animals &#8212; the separation of Jacob&#8217;s developing flock from Laban&#8217;s. The covenant community&#8217;s distinctiveness from the surrounding world is the type of the church&#8217;s calling: &#8220;Do not conform to the pattern of this world&#8221; (Rom 12:2); &#8220;Come out from them and be separate, says the Lord&#8221; (2 Cor 6:17); &#8220;you are a chosen people, a royal priesthood, a holy nation, God&#8217;s special possession&#8221; (1 Pet 2:9). Christ himself is &#8220;holy, blameless, pure, set apart from sinners&#8221; (Heb 7:26), and through his holiness calls his people into their distinctive covenant identity.</p>",
"41": "<p>Whenever the stronger females were in heat, Jacob would place the branches in the troughs in front of the animals so they would mate near the branches &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s strategy of applying the branches selectively to the stronger animals. The discernment of when and where to apply the covenant strategy is the type of pastoral wisdom. Christ applies himself to the strong and the weak differently: he calls the strong to give up their strength for others (Mark 10:43&#8211;44: &#8220;whoever wants to be great among you must be your servant&#8221;) and lifts up the weak (Matt 11:28: &#8220;Come to me, all you who are weary and burdened&#8221;). The wise application of the covenant to each person&#8217;s situation is the shape of Christ&#8217;s pastoral ministry.</p>",
"42": "<p>But if the animals were weak, he would not place the branches there. So the weak animals went to Laban and the strong to Jacob &#8212; the separation of strong from weak, with the strong belonging to Jacob and the weak to Laban. The eschatological separation &#8212; sheep from goats (Matt 25:32), wheat from tares (Matt 13:30) &#8212; has its type in this separation. But the eschatological logic is reversed: it is not the humanly-strong who belong to Christ but the weak who trust in him. &#8220;God has chosen the weak things of the world to shame the strong&#8221; (1 Cor 1:27). The type&#8217;s separation by natural strength is transformed in the antitype&#8217;s separation by faith: those who recognize their weakness and trust Christ are the ones who belong to him.</p>",
"43": "<p>In this way Jacob grew exceedingly prosperous and came to own large flocks, female and male servants, and camels and donkeys &#8212; Jacob&#8217;s prosperity after 20 years of Laban&#8217;s exploitation. The covenant-bearer&#8217;s ultimate prosperity despite extended exploitation is the type of Christ&#8217;s exaltation after his humiliation: &#8220;Therefore God exalted him to the highest place and gave him the name that is above every name&#8221; (Phil 2:9). The seven-years-times-two of service followed by prosperity corresponds to the cross followed by the resurrection and exaltation. The covenant-bearer who suffers longest comes out most abundantly &#8212; the logic of the kingdom in which &#8220;many who are first will be last, and many who are last will be first&#8221; (Matt 19:30).</p>",
},
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis', existing)
    print('Genesis 29-30 mkt-christ written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
